Title: Linking forum posts - advchem-003-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
I wondered why the statement 'As the concentration of a reactant increases, the rate increases due to an increase in the number of collisions per second.' is correct. Doesn't the concentration of the reactant play no effects on the zero-order reaction?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Chan-tat Ng, my name is Niranjana and I am a teaching assistant for this course. This statement is talking about Le Chatelier's principle. If you increase the concentration of a reactant, to reestablish equilibrium the reaction rate will increase to make more products. Therefore, the reaction rate increasing is referring to the reaction trying to reach equilibrium (by Le Chatelier's princple), it is not referring to the order of the reaction. I hope this helps answer your question. Best wishes for completing the course! Best, Niranjana

Input.posts:
In part4 of the 1.Kinetics problem one asks for: Determine the rate law and rate constant for the following reaction while the solutions ends by giving orders (rate constant is not calculated): This gives a rate law of Rate = k[X]^2[Y] I calculated k = 1600 [1/(SM^2)], but wanted to check if it's correct
Upvotes:
0
I believe the answer you are looking for is posted in the solution downloads... To determine the rate constant at this temperature, take a set of experimental data, plug in the values, and solve for k. In this solution, the first set of experimental data is used. Rate = k[X]^2 *[Y] 0.0016 M/s = k[0.01 M][0.01 M]^2 0.0016 M/s = k(0.000001 M^3) 1.6 × 10^3 s^-1*M^-2 = k The best value for k would be obtained by performing the above calculation for each set of experimental data and averaging the values together.
Upvotes:
0
In the solutions for # 2 of the\xA0Obtaining a Rate Law from Experimental Data practice problem, it tells you to re-arrange the rate law equation to get the order of A which is 2. What I did however was to double everything from the first experiment so that it would have the same concentration w/ B in the second experiment. After this, I calculated the order of 2 w/ my new rate and B concentration for the first experiment. I also got a 2. Does this really work or was it just coincidence?
Upvotes:
0
No Amber.\xA0 It does not work like that.\xA0 I began to do the same thing that you did until I reviewed the answer video.\xA0 It ends up that there is no constant for B.\xA0 So you have to solve for B first, holding A constant with experiment 1 and 2.\xA0 You will find B to be second order.\xA0 Then solve for A using the rate equation.\xA0 A is first order.\xA0 The rate = k = [A][B]^2.

Input.posts:
In part4 of the 1.Kinetics problem one asks for: Determine the rate law and rate constant for the following reaction while the solutions ends by giving orders (rate constant is not calculated): This gives a rate law of Rate = k[X]^2[Y] I calculated k = 1600 [1/(SM^2)], but wanted to check if it's correct
Upvotes:
0
I believe the answer you are looking for is posted in the solution downloads... To determine the rate constant at this temperature, take a set of experimental data, plug in the values, and solve for k. In this solution, the first set of experimental data is used. Rate = k[X]^2 *[Y] 0.0016 M/s = k[0.01 M][0.01 M]^2 0.0016 M/s = k(0.000001 M^3) 1.6 × 10^3 s^-1*M^-2 = k The best value for k would be obtained by performing the above calculation for each set of experimental data and averaging the values together.

After this, I calculated the order of 2 w/ my new rate and B concentration for the first experiment. I also got a 2. Does this really work or was it just coincidence?
Upvotes:

No Amber.\xA0 It does not work like that.\xA0 I began to do the same thing that you did until I reviewed the answer video.\xA0 It ends up that there is no constant for B.\xA0 So you have to solve for B first, holding A constant with experiment 1 and 2.\xA0 You will find B to be second order.\xA0 Then solve for A using the rate equation.\xA0 A is first order.\xA0 The rate = k = [A][B]^2.
